.ce
HBUILD6
.ce
Model 4/4D/4P Hard Disk Initialization System
.ce
16-Dec-84	 Revised 27-Jul-86
.ce
Copyright 1984, 1986 fdiv, All Rights Reserved.



.ps 10
.vs 11
HBUILD6 allows the Model 4P user to start the system from a hard
disk drive without using a start-up diskette.  This system is 
compatible with LS-DOS 6.3 and TRSDOS 6.2 operating systems and is
invisible to application packages.

The Model 4 and 4D owner may also use this product if the "C" or "D" ROM is
replaced with the "X" or "XD" ROM which is capable of booting from a hard disk drive.


\s+2Requirements\s-2

HBUILD6 is designed to be used with the ST506 hard disk driver that is
provided by Radio Shack (TRSHD6).  Other disk drivers may also work but cannot be
supported.

If you used the Radio Shack HARDGEN utility to initialize the hard disks
and included the operating system on the hard disk, your system should
be ready to be converted.

If you used HARDGEN and did not include the system on the hard disk, you
can convert one of the data drives to a system drive, or
reinitialize the system. (See "Converting a Data drive to a
System drive" for more information.)  If you decide to reinitialize the
drives, be sure to save all of your files before starting
the process.

HBUILD6 requires a LS-/TRS-DOS 6 logical drive to be on the first physical
drive.   It must also be located on head 1 of the drive.  (This may not be
the case if there is more than one operating system on your hard
disks.)  This logical drive must contain the LS-DOS 6.3 or
TRSDOS 6.2 operating system and currently be defined as logical Drive 0.
The HARDGEN utility always assures that this is the case if you included
the operating system on the hard disk drive.


\s+2Installing the Hard Disk Boot Track\s-2

.in .5i
.ti -.5i
1.	Start your system with the hard disk start-up diskette as you normally do.

.ti -.5i
2.	At the LS-/TRS-DOS Ready prompt, remove the start-up diskette
from floppy Drive 0.

.ti -.5i
3.	Insert the \fBHard Disk Boot Initialization\fR diskette into Drive 0
and close the drive door.

.ti -.5i
4.	Make sure the write-protect light is off on the primary hard disk
drive, the drive with the key-switch.

.ti -.5i
5.	Type:
	\fLHBUILD6 \fR 
.bx "ENTER"
.br

.ti -.5i
6.	After several seconds, HBUILD6 displays:

		\fLHard Disk Boot Track Installed Successfully\fR

(If HBUILD6 does not display this message, it displays an
error message.  See "Error Messages" for information
on how you should proceed.)

.ti -.5i
7.	If there were no errors, remove the diskette from Drive 0.

.ti -.5i
8.	Press RESET.  After a few seconds the system starts and prompts
for the date, time or displays the DOS Ready prompt.

.in .0i
Your hard disk boot installation is complete.  Store the 
\fBHard Disk Boot Initialization\fR
diskette in a safe place.  You will need this diskette if you ever reformat
your hard disks or upgrade the operating system.  To install a new operating
system or reformat your hard disks you will need to repeat this procedure to
restore the hard disk boot capability.




.ce
Page  1
.bp
.sp .5i
\s+2Error Messages\s-2

HBUILD6 performs several checks to make sure your system is configured so it
can use a hard disk boot.  If it finds anything wrong, it displays
the following messages.  If you receive any of these messages,
HBUILD6 quits and does not modify 
your hard disks.  
Each error message listed has information on what to do to correct the
problem.  After performing the action called for, run HBUILD6 again.
HBUILD6 displays only one error per run.  If there is more than one problem,
you will get the second error message when you rerun HBUILD6.

There are two types of errors - fatal errors and warnings.  Fatal errors
are preceded by a question mark (?).  Warnings are preceded
by a percent sign (%).  When you receive a warning, HBUILD6 asks if you
want to proceed with the installation.  If you receive a warning, proceed with
installation, and the hard disk boot does not boot by itself,
restart the machine using the start-up diskette and type:

	\fLBACKUP SYS0/SYS:\fRs\fL :0 (S,I)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

at the LS/TRSDOS Ready prompt.
(:s is the logical drive number of the floppy drive.)  This
command erases all of the
changes made by HBUILD6 and restores your system to its original state.
(It is possible to receive a warning and fatal error message.
In that case, correct the error and try again.  You may find that
correcting the fatal error corrects the warning as well.)

.in .5i
.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?Can't read boot track on hard disk.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	This means that some or all of Track 0 is unreadable.  This
area of the hard disk is not normally referenced and may have
been unreadable for some time.  Possible causes are
static or the age of the drive.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	Save all of the files on the hard disk to floppy disks and reformat
the hard disk.  When formatting is complete, restore your files
to the hard disk and rerun HBUILD6.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL%Drive 0 contains a SYSGEN file which may prevent
 the hard disk boot from functioning properly.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	A SYSGEN file is present on the hard disk drive.  Normally this file
has no use because the system uses the SYSGEN file on the start-up
diskette before switching control to the hard disk.  When the hard disk
boot is installed, this SYSGEN
file could be used and may conflict with some of the parameters that the
hard disk boot sets up, particularly if it was created on an earlier
version of the operating system.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	Remove the SYSGEN file by typing:	\fLSYSGEN (DRIVE=0,NO)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br
Rerun HBUILD6.  After the hard disk boot is installed,
you can boot on your hard disk and set up a new SYSGEN file.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?Logical Drive 0 is not on the hard disk.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	The system is currently using a floppy drive as
the system drive (Drive 0).  To use HBUILD6
the current system drive must be on the hard disk.  In addition,
logical Drive 0 must be on physical Drive 1 (primary drive), Head 1
(ones-based.)

.ti -.5i
Cure:	If you have a hard disk startup diskette that makes the hard disk
the system drive, boot the system using that diskette.
Rerun HBUILD6.  If you don't have a hard disk startup diskette,
prepare one using HARDGEN or follow the procedure
described in the \fIHard Disk System Startup\fR manual (supplied with the
\fITRSDOS Disk System Owner's Manual\fR.)


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL%This operating system may not be compatible with
 this version of the hard disk boot.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	The operating system that is running is not the
same version that HBUILD6 was written for.  The
hard disk boot may not work or may not install.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	You can upgrade to LS-DOS 6.3 or TRSDOS 6.2 by reinitializing you hard
disk drives.  Be sure to save all of the files on the hard disk drives
to floppy diskettes before using the HARDGEN utility that comes with
TRSDOS 6.2.
You can try installing HBUILD6 on your current system despite the
warning, and if it does not work,
remove the hard disk boot from your system by following the steps
in the "Removing the Hard Disk Boot".
.in 0i

.ce
Page  2
.bp
.sp .5i
.in .5i
.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?The hard disk driver has not been installed on this system.
 Install the driver. After the hard disk drives are initialized
 and contain a system, rerun HBUILD6.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	HBUILD6 cannot locate the hard disk driver in memory.  This message
may also be caused by using an alien hard disk driver that HBUILD6 cannot
recognize.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	If you are running under hard disk control, press RESET
and try again.  If not, start the system using the hard disk
start-up diskette and rerun HBUILD6.  If you are using a hard disk driver
other than the one provided by Radio Shack, HBUILD6 cannot be used.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?This program can only be used on a Model 4P system.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	This program cannot be used on a Model II, 12 or 16.
It can be used on a Model 4 or 4D with the "X" or "XD"
ROM.  HBUILD6 makes a check for these ROMs.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	If you are using a Model 4, you must install a new "X" ROM.
If you are using a Model 4D, you must install a new "XD" ROM.
If HBUILD6 displays this message on a Model 4P, reboot the system and rerun
HBUILD6.  If it fails again, it may indicate a hardware problem.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?The hard disk was not the first driver or filter installed
 on this system.  Restart your system and install the
 hard disk driver before you use any other driver or filter.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	The hard disk driver must be located in a particular position
in memory for HBUILD6 to work properly.  If you have loaded a
different filter or driver before you initialized your hard
disks, the hard disk driver is not the first module
in memory.  Drivers and filters can be loaded by a SYSGEN file
or using the SET or SYSTEM (DRIVER=) commands.
Other drivers and filters include COM/DVR, FORMS/FLT,
CLICK/FLT and KSM/FLT.  An alien hard disk driver can also cause this error.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	If you used HARDGEN to initialize your hard disks, you must rerun
that procedure.  To insure that no other drivers are used
between the time you press RESET and the time you run HARDGEN,
press RESET and let the system start HARDGEN automatically.
If you have files on your hard disk, be sure to save
them to floppy disks before running HARDGEN.  If you have the JCL
file that was produced by HARDGEN (usually left on the start-up
diskette), then boot from the start-up disk while holding 
down the 
.bx "CLEAR"
\& key.  Then you may enter just the SYSTEM
commands from that file and avoid reformatting the drive.  Once this
is done, rerun HBUILD6.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?The system drive must be on the logical drive that
 starts on Head 1 of physical Drive 1 (primary drive).\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	The boot ROM is responsible for starting the system.
It reads a single sector of the boot track and loads
it into memory.  It always looks at physical Drive 1, Head 1
for that sector.  Therefore, the system drive must also
start there.  (If you used HARDGEN and did not manually assign
heads to logical drives, you won't get this error.)

.ti -.5i
Cure:	Rerun HARDGEN, allowing it to build the drives.  If
you want to build the drives manually, make sure that the system
drive starts on Head 1 of the primary drive and rerun HBUILD6.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?SYS0/SYS does not exist on Drive 0. Use BACKUP to place 
 all of the system files on Drive 0 and rerun this program.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	Sometimes SYS0/SYS is deleted from the hard disk because it
isn't needed after the system is started.  It is only used
during the boot procedure.  Because the system is starting
from the hard disk, SYS0/SYS is now required.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	Move all of the system files from the start-up diskette to
the hard disk by typing:

	\fLBACKUP SYS:\fRs\fL :0 (S,I)\fR 
.bx "ENTER"
.br

where :s is the logical drive number of the floppy drive.
Rerun HBUILD6.


.in 0i
.ce
Page  3
.bp
.sp .5i
.in .5i
.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?SYS0/SYS has more than 4 extents.  Use BACKUP to place
 SYS0/SYS on the hard disk and rerun this program.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	SYS0/SYS can have more than 4 extents if you used the COPY command
to put it on the hard disk.  This is an invalid configuration for
this file.  You must use BACKUP 
to place SYS0/SYS on a disk.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	Type:

	\fLBACKUP SYS0:\fRs\fL :0 (S,I)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

where :s is the logical drive number for the start-up diskette.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?BOOT/SYS is not installed properly on Drive 0.
 Use BACKUP with the SYS option to install BOOT/SYS.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	BOOT/SYS is a special file that moves to a new
drive when the BACKUP utility moves SYS0/SYS.  You must move
these two files at the same time.
In addition, BOOT/SYS must start in the first
granule of cylinder 0 on every logical drive.  

.ti -.5i
Cure:	Type:

	\fLBACKUP SYS0:\fRs\fL :0 (S,I)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

where :s is the logical drive number for the start-up diskette.  BACKUP
moves BOOT/SYS when it moves SYS0/SYS and assures that BOOT/SYS is
in its required location.
It is possible that another file is in the location where
BOOT/SYS must reside.  If so, BACKUP quits.
If you get an error while executing this command, 
save all of the files on the hard disk to floppy disks
and initialize the hard disk drive using HARDGEN.
After formatting is complete, rerun HBUILD6.  Then restore your
files.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?Logical Drive 0 is write-protected.  Write-enable the
 drive and then rerun this program.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	Logical Drive 0 is software or hardware write-protected.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	Make sure the PROTECT lamp on the primary drive is off.  If
it is, depress PROTECT and rerun HBUILD6.  If the PROTECT lamp
was not on or you continue getting this error, type:

	\fLSYSTEM (DRIVE=0,WP=OFF)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

Rerun HBUILD6.


.ti -.5i
Error:	\fL?The DCT entry on logical Drive 0 does not match the
 entry in memory.\fR

.ti -.5i
Cause:	The start-up diskette you are using is not
the same one that was created when you initialized the hard
disks using HARDGEN.

Another possible cause is that the hard disks were formatted
before TRSDOS 6.2. 

If you have more than one Model 4/4P/4D system, you may be using the
start-up diskette for one of the other machines.

You may be using an old start-up diskette that 
does not match the way the hard disks were divided into
logical drives when they were last formatted.
When LS-/TRS-DOS 6 starts, the DCT from the start-up disk
is copied into memory.  The DCT describes the amount of space each
physical hard disk contains, and how much of that space is
assigned to each logical drive.  Operating the system with the
wrong DCT can cause files to be written on the wrong logical
drives, possibly erasing other files.

.ti -.5i
Cure:	Use the correct start-up diskette for this system and rerun HBUILD6.
If using the correct diskette does not solve problem, save all of
the files on the hard disk to floppy diskettes.  Reinitialize the
hard disk using HARDGEN and rerun HBUILD6.
.in .0i



.ce
Page  4
.bp
.sp .5i
\s+2Removing The Hard Disk Boot\s-2

To remove the hard disk boot anytime after running HBUILD6, follow these steps:

.in .5i
.ti -.5i
1.	Start the system with your hard disk start-up diskette.

.ti -.5i
2.	Make sure the primary hard disk drive is write-enabled.

.ti -.5i
3.	Type:		\fLBACKUP SYS0:\fRs\fL :0 (S,I)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

where :s is the logical drive number of the floppy drive that contains
the start-up diskette.  To display the logical drive number,
type \fLDEVICE\fR
.bx "ENTER"
\&.
.br

Look at the DEVICE display for the logical drive number
that contains the startup diskette.


.in 0i
After executing these commands, the hard disk no longer contains
any hard disk boot information. 


\s+2Converting a Data drive to a System drive\s-2

If you are not using your hard disk as a system drive, you must
build a system drive on the disk before you can boot without a floppy disk.
To do this, one logical drive is converted to the system drive.  
The two ways to create a system drive are:

Procedure 1
.in .5i

Save all of the files on your hard disk to floppy disks and
reinitialize the hard disk using HARDGEN.  If you have several
hard disk drives or numerous files, try to use Procedure 2.
To use Procedure 1, refer to the HARDGEN documentation when
reinitializing the hard disks.  When formatting is complete,
rerun HBUILD6.

.ti -.5i
or

.ti -.5i
Procedure 2

Identify the logical drive that can be converted to a system
drive and add the system files to that drive.
This procedure requires that you perform some detective-work and
the entering of several commands.

.ti -.5i
1.	Start up your system using the hard disk start-up diskette.
Insert the \fBHard Disk Boot Initialization\fR diskette in
floppy drive 0.

.ti -.5i
2.	Type:		\fLBASIC FINDZERO/BAS\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

to locate the logical drive that can be converted to a system drive.

.ti -.5i
3.	If the program reports that no logical drives can be used as the
system drive, the system cannot boot off the hard disk
as it is currently configured.  This could occur if you have more
than one operating system on your hard disk.  The only solution
is to save all of the files from your hard disk
to floppy disks and reinitialize the drive.  Be sure to save the
files in the parts of the hard disk drive that are
being used for CP/M or LDOS as a precaution.

If FINDZERO locates a drive that can be used, it displays
the drive number.

.ti -.5i
4.	At LS/TRS-DOS Ready, type:

	\fLBACKUP :0 :\fRd\fL (S,I,NEW)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

where :d is the drive number that FINDZERO displayed.  If BACKUP displays
an error, the hard disk drive may be write-protected.  Correct the
problem and repeat Step 4.
If there are too many files on the logical drive that has to be used,
copy some of the files to another logical drive and
then remove the copied files from drive d.
See your \fIDisk System Owner's Manual\fR for information on copying
and removing files.




.in 0i
.ce
Page  5
.bp
.sp .5i
.in .5i
.ti -.5i
5.	When BACKUP completes successfully, type:

	\fLSYSTEM (SYSTEM=\fRd\fL)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

where :d is the drive number that FINDZERO displayed.

.ti -.5i
6.	Remove the start-up diskette from the floppy drive and
insert the \fBLS-/TRS-DOS System and BASIC Interpreter\fR diskette.
Type:

	\fLBACKUP :\fRd\fL :0 (S,I,NEW)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

This copies any remaining files that were not present on the
start-up diskette, but are normally present on a system drive.
If LS-/TRS-DOS displays an error, refer to the instructions in Step 4.

You may now run HBUILD6.  Do not press RESET until you have
run HBUILD6.  If you encounter any errors and have to press RESET,
restart the system with the start-up diskette and type:

	\fLSYSTEM (SYSTEM=\fRd\fL)\fR
.bx "ENTER"
.br

At this point you can attempt to rerun HBUILD6.

.in 0i


